{{ Infobox Galaxy | image = UGC 1810 and UGC 1813 in Arp 273 (captured by the Hubble Space Telescope).jpg | image_size = 300px | caption=Image taken by the [[NASA]]/[[ESA]] [[Hubble Space Telescope]] shows Arp 273, a pair of interacting galaxies. | name = Arp 273 | type = | epoch = [[J2000]] | ra = {{RA|02|21|28.703}}<ref name="simbad">{{cite web | title=SIMBAD Astronomical Database | work=Results for Arp 273 | url=http://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/simbad/sim-basic?Ident=Arp+273 | accessdate=2011-04-20}}</ref> | dec = {{DEC|+39|22|32.65}}<ref name="simbad" /> | dist_ly = 300&nbsp;million ly | appmag_v = 13.7<ref>{{cite web|title=NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database|url=http://ned.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/objsearch?objname=Arp+273&extend=no&list_limit=5#BasicData_0|accessdate=2018-06-27}}</ref> | size_v = | constellation = [[Andromeda (constellation)|Andromeda]] | radius_ly = | absmag_v = | notes = | names = [[Uppsala General Catalogue|UGC]] 1810, [[Principal Galaxies Catalogue|PGC]] 8961, VV 323, Z 523-28, [[Atlas of Peculiar Galaxies|Arp]] 273, [[2MASS|2MASX]] J02212870+3922326, VV 323a, CGPG 0218.4+3909, [[Morphological Catalogue of Galaxies|MCG]]+06-06-023, ZW V 223,KPG 64a, UZC J022128.6+392231, Z 0218.4+3909<ref name="simbad"/> }}
'''Arp 273''' is a pair of [[interacting galaxies]], lying 300&nbsp;million [[light years]] away in the [[Andromeda (constellation)|constellation Andromeda]]. It was first described in the [[Atlas of Peculiar Galaxies]], compiled by [[Halton Arp]] in 1966.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interacting galaxies Arp 273|url=http://www.noao.edu/image_gallery/html/im0011.html|publisher=National Optical Astronomy Observatory|accessdate=2011-04-21}}</ref> The larger of the spiral galaxies, known as [[UGC 1810]], is about five times more massive than the smaller galaxy.<ref>{{cite web|title=A galactic rose highlights Hubble's 21st anniversary|url=http://www.spacetelescope.org/news/heic1107/|accessdate=2011-04-21|first1=Oli|last1=Usher|first2=Ray|last2=Villard|date=2011-04-20| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110516024825/http://spacetelescope.org/news/heic1107/| archivedate= 16 May 2011| deadurl= no}}</ref> It has a disc that is tidally distorted into a rose-like shape by the gravitational pull of the companion galaxy below it, known as [[UGC 1813]]. The smaller galaxy shows distinct signs of active star formation at its nucleus,<ref>{{cite web|title=NASA's Hubble Celebrates 21st Anniversary with "Rose" of Galaxies|url=http://hubblesite.org/newscenter/archive/releases/2011/11/video/b/|publisher=HubbleSite|accessdate=2011-04-21|date=2011-04-20}}</ref> and "it is thought that the smaller galaxy has actually passed through the larger one."<ref>{{cite web|title=A galactic rose highlights Hubble's 21st anniversary|url=http://www.physorg.com/news/2011-04-galactic-rose-highlights-hubble-21st.html|publisher=physorg.com|accessdate=2011-04-21|date=2011-04-21}}</ref>
