{{italic title}} In [[Taxonomy (biology)|biological classification]], a '''''species inquirenda''''' is a [[species]] of doubtful identity requiring further investigation.<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Glossary|title=International Code of Zoological Nomenclature|publisher=International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature|year=1999|edition=4th|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/hosted-sites/iczn/code/index.jsp?booksection=glossary&nfv=&mF=true|accessdate=2010-04-06}}</ref> The use of the term in English-language biological literature dates back to at least the early nineteenth century.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Botanical Register|first=Sydenham Teast|volume=5|last=Edwards|authorlink=Sydenham Edwards|location=London|year=1819|quote=[[Iris lacustris|lacustris]]. ''Nuttall gen.'' 1. 23; ''(species inquirenda)''.}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Glossary of scientific naming]] * ''[[Candidatus]]'', a proposed taxa based on incomplete evidence * ''[[incertae sedis]]'', a taxon of uncertain position in a classification * ''[[nomen dubium]]'', a name of unknown or doubtful application * [[Open nomenclature]], a system of notations used in taxonomy to indicate a taxonomist's judgement about taxon affinities
